== Japanese content ==
{{Coordinates list}}
'''Kuwada Shrine''' (くわだじんじゃ / くわたじんじゃ) is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}} listed in the ''{{ill|lt=Engishiki Jinmyocho|Q11064932|qid=Q11064932|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}'' for Kuwata District, {{ill|lt=Tanba Province|Q954511|qid=Q954511|1=Tanba Province}}. The following two shrines are treated as candidate shrines ({{ill|lt=ronsha|Q135022904|qid=Q135022904|1=Shikinai Ronsha}}):

* 1. {{ill|lt=Kuwada Shrine#Kuwada Shrine (Shinocho Yamamoto, Kameoka)|Q11537594|qid=Q11537594|lt=Kuwada Shrine|1=Kuwada Shrine}} (Shinocho Yamamoto, {{ill|lt=Kameoka|Q633996|qid=Q633996|1=Kameoka, Kyoto}}, {{ill|lt=Kyoto Prefecture|Q120730|qid=Q120730|1=Kyoto Prefecture}}) - former {{ill|lt=village shrine|Q134917284|qid=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}
* 2. {{ill|lt=Kuwada Shrine#Kuwada Shrine (Shinocho Umahori, Kameoka)|Q11537594|qid=Q11537594|lt=Kuwada Shrine|1=Kuwada Shrine}} (Shinocho Umahori, Kameoka, Kyoto) - former {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=mukakusha|1=UNKNOWN}}

=== Overview ===
The ''Engishiki Jinmyocho'' records "Kuwada Shrine, Kuwata District, Tanba Province." Two candidate shrines survive in Kameoka City. The Umahori shrine is sometimes said to be the former original site of the Yamamoto shrine, but the exact history is unclear.

Both are in eastern Kameoka near the entrance to {{ill|lt=Hozukyo Gorge|Q10887680|qid=Q10887680|1=Hozu Gorge}} on the right bank of the Oi River; {{ill|lt=Uketa Shrine|Q11631810|qid=Q11631810|1=Uketa Shrine}} stands across the river.

