'''Kuwada Shrine''' in Yamamoto is a Shinto shrine in Kameoka, Kyoto. It is a candidate Engishiki shrine; its former rank was village shrine.

=== Enshrined deities ===
; Main deity
* {{ill|lt=Ichikishimahime|Q11059454|qid=Q11059454|qid=Q11059454|lt=Ichikishimahime-no-Mikoto|1=Ichikishima-hime}}
; Additional deities
* {{ill|lt=Oyamakui|Q10935105|qid=Q10935105|lt=Oyamakui-no-Mikoto|1=Oyamakui no Kami}}
* {{ill|lt=Oyamazumi|Q386563|qid=Q386563|lt=Oyamazumi-no-Mikoto|1=Ōyamatsumi}}

=== History ===
Tradition says the deities, together with those of {{ill|lt=Kuwoyama Shrine|Q11650775|qid=Q11650775|1=Kuwayama Shrine}}, opened a channel through Hozukyo to reclaim the former lake area of the {{ill|lt=Kameoka Basin|Q11181997|qid=Q11181997|1=Kameoka Basin}}. The site at the basin entrance was politically important, and the Hata clan is said to have advanced here early.<ref name=setsumei/> Shrine tradition also links the old place-name "Tanba" to "Taniba."<ref name=kameoka>''Kameoka Shrine Gazetteer'', Kuwada Shrine section.</ref>

The shrine buildings burned in the Tenmei era (1781-1789).<ref name=chosayama/> Until 1873, it reportedly shared the name "Uketa Shrine (Ukita Shrine)" with the shrine across the river.<ref name=setsumei>On-site explanatory board.</ref> It was ranked village shrine in June 1873 and officially used the name "Kuwada Shrine" in June 1877.<ref name=chosayama/>

